  "prompt": "Why are garage sales are not common in India?",
  "response": "Garage sales are not common in India for several reasons:\n\n1. Cultural differences\n- Indian culture values keeping and preserving items rather than selling used goods\n- Giving away or selling used items is often seen as a sign of low economic status\n- People tend to pass down items to family members or within their social network\n\n2. Space constraints\n- Most urban Indian homes have limited storage space\n- People generally tend to use items until they are completely worn out\n- Less excess inventory compared to Western countries\n\n3. Economic factors\n- Lower middle-class and working-class populations often repair and reuse items\n- Recycling and repurposing are more common than selling used goods\n- Secondhand markets like local kabadiwallas (scrap dealers) exist for selling used items\n\n4. Alternative selling platforms\n- Online platforms like OLX, Quikr, and Facebook Marketplace are more prevalent\n- These digital platforms offer easier and more convenient ways to sell used items\n\n5. Social perception\n- Selling personal belongings at a public sale might be considered socially awkward\n- People prefer more private and discreet methods of selling used items\n\n6. Limited suburban culture\n- Garage sales are typically associated with suburban neighborhoods\n- Indian cities have different residential structures compared to Western countries\n\nThese factors contribute to the relative rarity of garage sales in India.",
